	<transcript sound="sound1"><![CDATA[In this module, we'll look at food safety law and enforcement.<br /><br />We'll briefly cover the objectives of food safety regulations and the responsibilities of food handlers and food business operators.<br /><br />We'll learn about the roles and powers of authorised officers and the due diligence defence under all legislation.<br /><br />You'll need approximately fifteen minutes to complete this module.]]></transcript>

	<transcript sound="sound2"><![CDATA[Most food safety legislation is imposed directly by the European Union in the form of regulations.<br /><br />Food safety legislation is required to set minimum standards for food business operators and food premises which reduces the risk of foodborne illness.<br /><br />It also prohibits the sale of contaminated food, thereby protecting public health.<br /><br />The regulations control the hygiene standards of food premises, food equipment and food handlers.<br /><br />They are concerned with preventing food contamination and promoting correct temperature control.<br /><br />Furthermore all food businesses must have a food safety management system, based of the principles of HACCP, in place.<br /><br />Also all food businesses must register with the local authority at least twenty eight days before they begin trading.<br /><br />Remember; ignorance of the law is not a defence in the event of prosecution; so you must make special efforts to understand it.]]></transcript>
	
		
